    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="258"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Potsdam/7–1445</note>
                <head>No. 258<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DJC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dunn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d258fn1">Printed from a carbon copy on which there is an
                        uncertified typed signature.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]<note n="2" xml:id="d258fn2">For other
                            extracts from this memorandum, see documents Nos. 140, 218, 234, 319,
                            351, 379, 404, 470, 519, 635, 645, 678, and 708.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Potsdam</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-14">July 14,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the Secretary</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CHSA1">Sir Alexander Cadogan</persName>, Permanent
                    Under-Secretary at the Foreign Office, called this afternoon and discussed for
                    two hours in a preliminary way a number of matters on the agenda of the
                        Conference.<note n="3" xml:id="d258fn3">For a list of persons present at
                        this meeting, see <ref target="#d234fn3">document No. 234, footnote
                        3</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">15. <hi rend="italic">Yalta Declaration on Liberated
                    Areas</hi>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CHSA1">Sir Alexander</persName> felt that we had more
                    faith in the Declaration than he, but said the <gloss target="#t_UK1">U.
                        K.</gloss> Delegation would “come along behind us” in any effort to secure
                    its implementation. In justifying his government’s preference for the conclusion
                    of peace treaties, <persName corresp="#p_CHSA1">Sir Alexander</persName>
                    explained that, contrary to our situation with regard to <persName
                        corresp="#p_I2">Italy</persName>, his government cannot resume diplomatic
                    relations with a country with which it is at war.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">James Clement Dunn</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
